        </p>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl font-light text-charcoal tracking-wide mb-6">
          Types of Visas: A Brief Overview
        </h3>
        <p class="font-sans text-base font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Argentina residency can be obtained through several routes. The <a href="/visa/investor" class="text-bronze hover:underline font-normal">Inversionista (investor) visa</a> is for those who make a qualifying investment in an Argentine business or venture and is the main route for clients who want to <strong class="font-normal text-charcoal">invest in Argentina</strong> while securing <strong class="font-normal text-charcoal">Argentina residency</strong>. The <a href="/visa/retiree" class="text-bronze hover:underline font-normal">Pensionado (retirement) visa</a> is for applicants with a verifiable monthly pension. The <a href="/visa/rentista" class="text-bronze hover:underline font-normal">Rentista visa</a> is for those who can demonstrate stable passive income. Each of these leads to temporary and then permanent residency; after two years of permanent residency, you can pursue the <strong class="font-normal text-charcoal">Argentina golden visa</strong> path and apply for citizenship. For full details on requirements and process, see our <a href="/visa-options" class="text-bronze hover:underline font-normal">visa options</a> and <a href="/citizenship" class="text-bronze hover:underline font-normal">citizenship</a> pages.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl font-light text-charcoal tracking-wide mb-6">
          Investment Advantages of the Golden Visa Path
        </h3>
        <p class="font-sans text-base font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Choosing to <strong class="font-normal text-charcoal">invest in Argentina</strong> as part of your residency strategy aligns your capital with a clear immigration outcome. Qualifying investments can include real estate, business ventures, or other instruments that meet Migraciones requirements. Property prices in many Argentine cities remain well below those in major North American and European hubs, so the same capital often buys more—whether you intend to live in the property, rent it, or use it as part of a broader portfolio. The <strong class="font-normal text-charcoal">Argentina golden visa</strong> path does not require a fixed minimum investment in the way some European programs do; what matters is that you establish and maintain residency, meet the investment or income criteria of your chosen visa, and comply with the two-year residency period before applying for citizenship. That makes the program accessible to a broader range of investors while still offering a serious, rule-based route to a second passport and a lasting connection to Argentina.
        </p>
